redin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kilbride","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Kieran, Aidan.","Irish (Connacht) and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Brighde</b> (Irish) or <b>Mac Gille Brighde</b> (Scottish) ‘son of the servant of (Saint) Brigit’, also often shortened and Anglicized as   McBride  . The name <i>Brigit</i> means ‘exalted’. Brigit was originally a pagan goddess, many of whose attributes, such as a sacred fire, became attached to the historical figure of Saint Brigit of Kildare (452–523), founder of the first Irish convent.","Scottish: habitational name from any of various places with this name, from Gaelic <i>Cill Bríghde</i> ‘church of Saint Brigit’ (<i>cill</i> being from Latin <i>cella</i> ‘room, cell’), for example Kilbride in Lanarkshire."]},{"name":"McBryde","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   McBride  ."]},{"name":"McBridge","meanings":["(1997: 111;2007: 409; 2010: NA)","Irish: variant of   McBride  , representing the original Gaelic pronunciation."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Bethoca McBride was born in 1075, in Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Andrew McBrad, was 50 and her mother, Lady McBrad, was 50. She had at least 1 son with Macbeotha McFinlay. She died in 1145, in her hometown, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1075–1145":"1075–1145","1048–1093":"1048–1093","1090–1152":"1090–1152","1025–Male":"1025–Surnud","1025–Female":"1025–Surnud","1090":"1090","1048":"1048","1025":"1025","1145":"1145","1075":"1075","1152":"1152","1093":"1093","Scotland":"Scotland","Ross-shire, Scotland":"Ross-shire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland":"Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1075–1145":"1075–1145","1048–1093":"1048–1093","1090–1152":"1090–1152","1025–Male":"1025–Kuollut","1025–Female":"1025–Kuollut","1090":"1090","1048":"1048","1025":"1025","1145":"1145","1075":"1075","1152":"1152","1093":"1093","Scotland":"Scotland","Ross-shire, Scotland":"Ross-shire, Skotl